he humanities and the social sciences over the interwar years, as well as in World War II sites and practices. This book explores the decision-making processes and visions of knowledge production at the foundations, the Social Science Research Council, and others charged with guiding the intellectual and institutional development of Middle East studies. Ultimately, Field Notes uncovers how area studies as an academic field was actually built-a process replete with contention, anxiety, dead ends, and consequences both unanticipated and unintended.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArea studieszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Council of Learned Societies. 4aCold War. 4aMiddle East studies. 4aSocial Science Research Council. 4aarea studies. 4ahumanities. 4aphilanthropic foundations. 4asocial science. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479958440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799584.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles